{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479107"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.75,0.04,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69873"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"11477"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44234"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her three-year-old daughter. She is new to the practice, having recently moved to the area. She reports her daughter has had eight episodes of seizures in the past two months, characterised by eye rolling, limb stiffening, and post-ictal drowsiness lasting 30 minutes. Each episode occurred when only the mother was present. The child has been seen at three different general practices and two emergency departments during this period. Previous investigations including electroencephalogram, magnetic resonance imaging of the brain, metabolic studies, and toxicology screens have been normal. The mother is a registered nurse in a paediatric intensive care unit and provides detailed medical descriptions of the episodes, including precise timing and medication doses administered. She appears overly concerned and requests additional tests, specifically genetic testing for rare epilepsy syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe child has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Development is age-appropriate. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is normal. Review of previous medical records reveals multiple presentations for various other symptoms including unexplained bleeding, respiratory distress, and fevers, all of which resolved spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the presentations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psychogenic non-epileptic seizures","Factitious disorder imposed on another","Dravet syndrome","Parental anxiety disorder","Covert medication administration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents multiple red flags suggestive of factitious disorder imposed on another (FDIA) that may be encountered in general practice. The key features include multiple presentations to different healthcare providers, normal investigations, symptoms only occurring in the presence of the caregiver, a caregiver with sophisticated medical knowledge who appears overly concerned, and a pattern of various unexplained symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactitious disorder imposed on another\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious form of child abuse where a caregiver fabricates, exaggerates, or induces physical or psychological symptoms in a person under their care. Healthcare professionals, particularly those working in paediatric settings, are overrepresented among perpetrators. The detailed medical knowledge and the pattern of multiple unexplained symptoms strongly suggest FDIA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic non-epileptic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E would be extremely rare in a three-year-old child. These typically occur in older children or adolescents and are often associated with psychological trauma or stress. The exclusive occurrence in the mother\u0027s presence makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDravet syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe genetic epilepsy syndrome that typically presents in the first year of life with prolonged seizures triggered by fever. While the mother\u0027s request for genetic testing might suggest this, the normal investigations and lack of documented seizures in the presence of healthcare providers make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParental anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E might lead to excessive concern about a child\u0027s health, but would not explain the pattern of multiple different symptoms occurring only in the mother\u0027s presence. Additionally, healthcare workers with anxiety typically recognise normal findings and are reassured by negative investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECovert medication administration\u003C/strong\u003E is actually a subset of FDIA rather than a separate diagnosis. While this might be the mechanism by which some of the symptoms are induced, it represents the method rather than the underlying disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGeneral practitioners should maintain detailed documentation of all consultations, consider early involvement of child protection services, and work within a multi-disciplinary framework including paediatricians, mental health professionals, and social workers. The safety of the child is paramount, and separation from the perpetrator may be necessary while the investigation proceeds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Factitious disorder imposed on another (FDIA) is characterised by caregivers fabricating or inducing illness in others under their care, with healthcare workers being overrepresented among perpetrators.","Key diagnostic features in factitious disorder imposed on another (FDIA) include symptoms only occurring in caregiver presence, multiple presentations to different healthcare providers, and normal investigations.","General practitioners should maintain detailed documentation and have a low threshold for involving child protection services when factitious disorder imposed on another (FDIA is suspected."],"references":["Court A, Gillam L. Factitious disorders by proxy: when parents inappropriately drive medical investigation and treatment. Grand Rounds Online. 2017 Apr 12. Available from: https://blogs.rch.org.au/grandrounds/2017/04/12/factitious-disorders-by-proxy-when-parents-inappropriately-drive-medical-investigation-and-treatment/","Fish E, Bromfield L, Higgins D. A new name for Munchausen Syndrome by Proxy: defining fabricated or induced illness by carers. Child Abuse Prev Issues. 2005;(23):1-11. Available at: https://aifs.gov.au/cfca/sites/default/files/publication-documents/issues23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69873"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69873"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-16T20:33:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-16T20:43:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12297"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"head